✅ 1. Install Git & open Git Bash
Git Bash comes with Git for Windows. Once installed, open Git Bash anywhere you want to work.

✅ 2. Configure Git so GitHub knows who you are
GitHub requires your name and email for commits.

Code
git config --global user.name "Marcus Perez"
git config --global user.email "your-email@example.com"
(These values appear in your GitHub commit history.)

✅ 3. Create or clone a repository
Option A — Start a new local repo
Code
mkdir my-project
cd my-project
git init

Option B — Clone an existing GitHub repo
Code
git clone https://github.com/username/repository.git
cd repository

✅ 4. Connect your local folder to GitHub
If you created a repo on GitHub first, copy its HTTPS URL and run:

Code
git remote add origin https://github.com/username/repository.git
git remote -v
This links your local Git Bash repo to the online GitHub repo.

✅ 5. Stage & commit your changes
Add files:

Code
git add .
Commit:

Code
git commit -m "Initial commit"
✅ 6. Push your code to GitHub
Send your commits to the online repo:

Code
git push -u origin main
The -u flag sets origin/main as your default upstream branch.

✅ 7. Pull updates from GitHub
If someone else changed the repo (or you changed it online):

Code
git pull origin main

🔐 8. Authenticate with GitHub
GitHub requires either:

Option A — HTTPS + Personal Access Token (recommended)
Git will prompt you for a password → enter your GitHub PAT, not your actual password.

Option B — SSH keys
Generate a key and add it to GitHub:

Code
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your-email@example.com"
Then add the public key to GitHub under Settings → SSH and GPG keys.

🎯 Your Git Bash → GitHub workflow (copy/paste)
Code
git status
git add .
git commit -m "update"
git push
This is the exact loop you’ll use daily.
